article.description:
Nykesha Sales had 22 points and Taj McWilliams-Franklin pulled down two key rebounds and scored three
points in the closing seconds as the Connecticut Sun beat the Houston Comets 70-66 on Friday.
article.headline: Comets comeback comes up short
article.linkText: Sales outduels Swoopes as Sun stays hot at home
article.story:
UNCASVILLE, Conn. (AP) -- Every time the Connecticut Sun needed a
clutch basket, Asjha Jones delivered.

The reserve forward scored 14 points, including consecutive
jumpers in the closing minutes, to help the Sun hold off a late
rally and beat the Houston Comets 70-66 on Friday night. The
victory kept the Eastern Conference-leading Sun perfect at home
this season.

"When I go out there I'm trying to run up and down the court
and take some shots and try to open things up," Jones said.

She did, going 7-for-12 from the floor. Jones, who played her
college ball 30 minutes away at UConn, came in to spell 7-foot-2
Margo Dydek.

"I kept wanting to put Margo back in the game, but it was one
of those things where Asjha just kept making big plays," coach
Mike Thibault said.

The Sun (13-4) are 7-0 at home this season and 12-0 at Mohegan
Sun arena since closing out last season with five straight home
wins.

Nykesha Sales had 22 points and Taj McWilliams-Franklin pulled
down two key rebounds and scored three points in the closing
seconds to seal the win. The victory also snapped Connecticut's
two-game losing streak.

"This win is a confidence builder," McWilliams-Franklin said.
"It was definitely something we needed to get us out of the
doldrums of all those losses."

The Comets were coming off a 68-65 overtime loss to New York and
have now lost two straight after winning six in a row.

Sheryl Swoopes led the Comets (10-7) with 21 points. Her jumper
with 4:54 left pulled Houston to within one at 63-62, but Jones
countered with a jumper from the top of the lane.

"We doubled the ball. That's what we did the whole second half.
We didn't want to give (Jones) the open shot, but she got it and
made it," Swoopes said. "We have to go to her a lot faster."

After the teams traded buckets, Kristen Rasmussen hit a driving
layup for Houston with 1:26 left to get the Comets to just one
back.

Houston got the ball right back on Janeth Arcain's steal, but
Swoopes' off-balance shot missed and McWilliams-Franklin grabbed
the rebound.

On Connecticut's next possession, McWilliams-Franklin hit an
inside bucket with 11.3 seconds left to give Connecticut a 69-66 lead.

The Comets had one last shot and with time running out, Arcain
fired up a 3-point attempt that missed.

McWilliams-Franklin came down with the rebound, was fouled and
hit one of two free throws to end the scoring. She finished with
nine points, four boards and a blocked shot.

Lindsay Whalen added 14 points and had five assists for
Connecticut. Dydek finished with six points, seven rebounds and
three blocked shots.

Michelle Snow 10 points for Houston and matched her season-high
with 12 rebounds. Arcain finished with 14 points.

"We didn't execute our game plan," Snow said. "All five
players have to be on the same page and they made some key baskets
that really hurt us."

Swoopes had 13 points in the first half. Her pair of free throws
with 16:07 in the half gave Houston its only lead of the game at
8-5. But Whalen countered with a 3-pointer to start an 8-0 run and
regain control. Connecticut led by nine in the period and took a
41-34 lead at the break. Whalen and Sales combined for 23 points in
the first half.

"We did a good job of coming back," Houston coach Van
Chancellor said. "I'm really proud of our team, but Connecticut
really executed down the stretch."

Connecticut breezed through the first part of the season and
after dropping its first two after the All-Star break, a tight game
like this was what the Sun needed, Thibault said.

"It was the first time since the playoffs where it came down to
the last minute," Thibault said. "I thought we got back to that
playoff mentality where we valued every possession."
